<subSubSection id="C372657C5741FFF0DFFAFD5F7D37FBA6" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BD736F75741FFF0DFFAFD5F7D9DFC7D" blockId="19.[151,1437,578,1290]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis id="B91CEAE55741FFF0DFFAFD5F7875FCCD" bold="true" box="[199,314,758,785]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Size medium, length 
<quantity id="4C909B125741FFF0DD05FD5F7B8DFCCE" box="[568,706,758,786]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.15" metricValueMax="3.5" metricValueMin="2.8" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="3.15" valueMax="3.5" valueMin="2.8">2.8–3.5 mm</quantity>
; dorsal ground color light to medium reddish brown with pattern of darker maculae (
<figureCitation id="13532A725741FFF0DE4AFCB2788EFCE9" box="[375,449,795,821]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–9" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1792,1817]" captionTargetBox="[354,1209,529,1746]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[346,1242,548,1765]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–9. Xanthonia species, dorsal habitus. 1) X. angulata (Bastrop Co., Texas); 2) X. dentata (Jeff Davis Co., Texas); 3) X. furcata (Wood Co., Texas); 4) X. nitida (Pecos Co., Texas); 5) X. parva (Kerr Co., Texas); 6) X. picturata (Robertson Co., Texas); 7) X. querci (Val Verde Co., Texas); 8) X. texana (Bandera Co., Texas); 9) X. villosula (Bossier Parish, Louisiana). Images to scale, scale bar = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3414688" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3414688/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Figs 3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13532A725741FFF0DEECFCB278BEFCE9" box="[465,497,795,821]" captionStart="FIGURES 76–78" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1320,1345]" captionTargetBox="[296,1319,474,1291]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[266,1322,474,1302]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 76–78. Xanthonia species, types and type labels. 76) X. texana; 77) X. querci; 78) X. furcata. Map 7. Distribution of Xanthonia texana." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3414704" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3414704/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">78</figureCitation>
); venter of body dark brown to black; pubescence of elytra composed of reclined hairs on intervals in single rows and appressed hairs arising from punctures shorter than erect hairs; ventral tooth of profemur obsolete to absent; lateral margins of all ventrites entire; median lobe of male genitalia gradually tapered distally, apex with deep, acute v-shaped incision with acutely pointed lobe on each side (
<figureCitation id="13532A725741FFF0DB4AFC2E7D8AFC7D" box="[1143,1221,903,929]" captionStart="FIGURES 64–75" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1513,1538]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,546,1494]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[189,1398,546,1494]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 64–75. Xanthonia species, en-face and lateral view of median lobe. 64) X. angulata (Washington, DC); 65–66) X. angulata (Mt. Vernon, Virginia); 67–68) (Bastrop State Park, Texas), 69); X. striata (Flatbush, New York); 70) X. striata (Nelson Co., Virginia); 71) X. striata (Wolfville, Maryland); 72–73) X. striata (Hanover, Pennsylvania); 74–75) X. furcata (Union Co., Illinois). All figures from Weisman (1960), except 67–68." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3414702" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3414702/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig 74</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
